      Redbox?!?
   =20
 =20
We  talked last month about Redbox Entertainment Inc., a company that (1) w=
ent public in October 2021 by merging with a special purpose acquisition co=
mpany at $10 per share, (2) traded as high as $17.93, (3) then traded down =
to $5.60, (4) then agreed to be acquired by Chicken Soup for the Soul Enter=
tainment Inc. for about $0.69 per share in stock, an 88% discount to its tr=
ading price, and (5) then traded down to $2.58 per share. That was weird! T=
wo weird things were:=09Why would the company agree to sell=C2=A0for $0.69 =
per share when it was trading at $5.60? (=E2=80=9CWe were bringing assets t=
hat were helpful in terms of the debt, cleaning up of the capital structure=
, access to new cash,=E2=80=9D Chicken Soup=E2=80=99s chief executive offic=
er   sort of explained.)=09Why would people=C2=A0buy stock for $2.58=C2=A0w=
hen it is going to be merged out of existence at $0.69?You might have told =
a story like =E2=80=9Cthe deal won=E2=80=99t close and the stock will shoot=
 up as people realize the great value of an independent Redbox,=E2=80=9D bu=
t there is no evidence for that; in fact Redbox=E2=80=99s controlling share=
holders had approved the deal so the odds of it falling apart are low.Or yo=
u might have told a story like =E2=80=9Cthe stock will trade down to $0.69 =
as people realize what is happening,=E2=80=9D but that story would have bee=
n wrong. Redbox has rallied. It=C2=A0closed at $9.47 yesterday, and was up =
again this morning; at noon today it was trading at about $12.89 on heavy v=
olume, tons of social-media enthusiasm=C2=A0and absolutely no news. Meanwhi=
le Chicken Soup=E2=80=99s stock hasn=E2=80=99t done much; it closed yesterd=
ay at $7.31, making=C2=A0the merger consideration =E2=80=94=C2=A00.087 Chic=
ken Soup shares per Redbox share =E2=80=94=C2=A0worth about $0.64 per Redbo=
x share. You can buy a Redbox share for $12.89 today, and when the merger c=
loses you=E2=80=99ll get 0.087 Chicken Soup shares. Or you can buy a whole =
Chicken Soup share today for $7.31, and when the merger closes you=E2=80=99=
ll still have a whole Chicken Soup share. One Chicken Soup share, which you=
 can buy for $7.31, is worth about 11 times as much as 0.087 Chicken Soup s=
hares, which you can buy for $12.89. Why?=C2=A0I dunno. But there are two l=
essons here. One is that the essential function of a meme stock is to be a =
 Schelling point: A meme stock is=C2=A0a stock that you want to buy because=
 other people want to buy it. How a stock becomes a meme stock is, to me, a=
 mysterious process, but there is no obvious reason that =E2=80=9Cpeople th=
ink it has a lot of fundamental value=E2=80=9D would be a particularly impo=
rtant part of the process. (Really, =E2=80=9Ca stock that you buy because o=
ther people want to buy it because it has good long-term cash flows=E2=80=
=9D is the opposite of a meme stock; that=E2=80=99s just a regular stock.)=
=C2=A0You want your meme stocks to be=C2=A0fun; you want the story to be vi=
vid; you want the online discussions where you egg each other on to buy the=
 stock to have a sense of drama and comedy. At Quartz last month, Scott Nov=
er wrote an article titled =E2=80=9CRedbox is the dumbest meme stock yet=E2=
=80=9D:On Reddit, there=E2=80=99s been chatter about a short squeeze, but o=
nly about 29% of Redbox=E2=80=99s public float has been sold short, accordi=
ng to data published by FactSet. Short squeezes work when so much of a comp=
any=E2=80=99s stock is shorted that when buyers drive it up, shorts have to=
 re-enter the market by buying new shares to cover their own loss, sending =
the stock even higher. (By contrast, 140% of GameStop=E2=80=99s float was s=
horted when retail traders took it to the moon in January 2021.)When the sa=
le to Chicken Soup for the Soul closes in the next few months, Redbox stock=
holders will be paid out at $.49 a share. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t see any =
scenario where an investor could make money, aside from the greater fool th=
eory,=E2=80=9D one financial analyst told Yahoo Finance.In other words, ret=
ailers might be pumping the stock and hoping to get out before the dumping =
starts. This trading activity appears to have nothing to do with movies, st=
reaming, or large red vending machines. Like other consumer-facing companie=
s that tap into retail trader nostalgia=E2=80=94like GameStop, AMC, Bed Bat=
h & Beyond, Blackberry, and even Blockbuster=E2=80=94Redbox is just another=
 momentary Wall Street meme. At least this one has an expiration date when =
the deal closes.Those attributes are all bad for, like, rational stock valu=
e, but good for memes:=09Trading the dumbest meme stock is much funnier tha=
n trading the forty-sixth-dumbest meme stock. Redbox is a very funny meme s=
tock! If you tell a traditional finance person =E2=80=9CI am buying GameSto=
p at $300,=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Chmm that seems high I dunno.=E2=
=80=9D If you tell them =E2=80=9CI am buying Redbox at $12.89=E2=80=9D they=
 will sputter and twitch and try to prove to you with math=C2=A0that it=E2=
=80=99s a mistake. That=E2=80=99s funnier!=09Having an expiration date make=
s this game more exciting and sillier. The problem with a regular meme stoc=
k is that eventually people will get bored; the finite expiration date here=
 limits that risk. The game has to end, and when it does, someone will be h=
olding quite a bag. It creates more immediate danger and excitement than a =
meme stock that could keep going up forever.Also to be fair once the deal c=
loses you could aways meme up the Chicken Soup stock, why not.The other les=
son=C2=A0is that the essential condition of a meme stock is limits to arbit=
rage. Any reasonable person would look at this price action and say: =E2=80=
=9CI should short 1 million shares of Redbox for $9.47, collecting $9.47 mi=
llion; then I should buy 87,000 shares of Chicken Soup for $7.31, spending =
$636,000, and then when the merger happens I will deliver those Chicken Sou=
p shares to close out my short and keep my $8.8 million of nearly risk-free=
 profit.=E2=80=9D But a sensible person would have said that back when Redb=
ox was trading at $2.58 last month, and if they had done that trade then, i=
t would have moved against them by millions of dollars by now and they prob=
ably would have been liquidated at a huge loss. Because there is no cap on =
the price of a meme stock, it is risky and unpleasant to short one, and the=
re is at least one high-profile case of a multibillion-dollar hedge fund  c=
losing down due to excessive shorting of meme stocks. Why bother, on a stoc=
k this small? (Also, relatedly, stock borrow in Redbox is scarce and expens=
ive, so it=E2=80=99s not exactly easy and costless to do this trade. Also, =
I mean, the merger could=C2=A0fall apart.) And so there are meme-y buyers t=
o push Redbox up, and no rational sellers to push it down, and the price sp=
irals up.The advanced move here would be for Redbox to do an at-the-market =
offering, selling a bunch of shares for $9.47 each to raise extremely cheap=
 cash for its soon-to-be owners at Chicken Soup. I think that would be a bi=
t too much? Other meme stocks have  done at-the-market offerings, and the U=
S Securities and Exchange Commission has  grumbled but allowed it. The SEC =
doesn=E2=80=99t like=C2=A0it when companies sell shares=C2=A0to excited ret=
ail investors for more than they=E2=80=99re worth, but it can=E2=80=99t rea=
lly police that; worth is subjective, and you can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0prove=C2=
=A0that the shares are selling for more than they=E2=80=99re worth.=C2=A0Do=
ing an at-the-market offering at $9.47 when you=E2=80=99ve signed a merger =
agreement to sell for $0.69 probably goes too far though.
