   =20
      Private markets are the new public markets
   =20
 =20
One widely accepted theory in financial markets is that liquid things are w=
orth more than illiquid things. If you know that you can sell an asset quic=
kly for roughly its fair price, you will be happier about buying it, so you=
 will pay more for it. Classically, private companies are supposed to becom=
e more valuable when they go public: You can trade public stock on the stoc=
k exchange relatively easily, which should make it more valuable than illiq=
uid private-company stock.There is a countervailing theory, one that  I ass=
ociate with Cliff Asness, that holds that illiquid things are worth more th=
an liquid things. The theory here is that investors do not like=C2=A0volati=
lity; they prefer steady returns to wild price swings. Stocks that trade fr=
equently in liquid public markets=C2=A0look=C2=A0volatile: Sometimes they g=
o up, but sometimes they go down. Private-company stocks=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=
 look volatile, because they don=E2=80=99t trade much, and when they do it =
is often in carefully orchestrated ways that give the impression of steadil=
y increasing prices. (Most people who buy private-company stocks buy them f=
rom the company in organized funding rounds, and if the market is bad the c=
ompany just won=E2=80=99t raise money.) An investor who wants returns with =
low volatility will prefer (and overpay for) illiquid assets: When times ar=
e good, the prices of those assets will go up and you will have a gain; whe=
n times are bad, they won=E2=80=99t trade and you won=E2=80=99t have to rec=
ognize a loss.And so when the market for tech stocks goes down, the market =
for=C2=A0private=C2=A0tech companies =E2=80=A6=C2=A0also goes down, in some=
 economic sense (it is harder for those companies to raise money), but argu=
ably doesn=E2=80=99t go down, in some accounting sense. Here's a  Bloomberg=
 News story about D1 Capital Partners, a hedge fund that does lots of publi=
c and private investing:D1 has told investors who selected a 50-50 mix of p=
ublic and private assets that the strategy lost 23% through May. The firm a=
ttributed most of the damage to public investments, which fell 44%. It mark=
ed down private assets only 8% -- including 0.05% last month. There=E2=80=
=99s a reason it wasn=E2=80=99t more dramatic: D1 assesses the value of its=
 private stakes quarterly, with only some exceptions in the interim. The ne=
xt round is due at the end of this month.While D1 will likely mark down som=
e of the companies in its portfolio, its biggest investment, SpaceX, is exp=
ected to be marked up by about 25% after a recent funding round, according =
to a person with knowledge of the firm=E2=80=99s thinking.When valuations t=
urn sharply downward, private markets can take six to nine months to settle=
 on new prices, said Ken Smythe, founder of Next Round Capital, which helps=
 institutional investors trade such assets. One reason is that sales tend t=
o stall after a plunge, with investors reluctant to lock in losses.=E2=80=
=9CThe secondary market is in a quandary because people can=E2=80=99t figur=
e out what stuff is worth right now,=E2=80=9D Smythe said. =E2=80=9CBuyers =
are demanding lower prices, making liquidity difficult for many of these na=
mes.=E2=80=9D Sellers, meanwhile, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t want to accept the=
 reality of how much less they=E2=80=99re worth now.=E2=80=9DIf you own pub=
lic stocks, you don=E2=80=99t get any choice about accepting that they=E2=
=80=99re worth less: You can look at the price on your screen, and if it=E2=
=80=99s down it's down. If you own private stocks, you can wait a bit. Mayb=
e they=E2=80=99ll go back up!=C2=A0Meanwhile at the Information, here is =
=E2=80=9CSecondary Markets Seize Up as Startup Insiders Dump Shares=E2=80=
=9D:The prices that some of the most richly valued private companies can fe=
tch have already plunged, with Stripe and Klarna shares changing hands at p=
rices roughly 40% lower than at the start of the year, according to data sh=
ared with The Information by ApeVue. The New York=E2=80=93based financial s=
tartup aggregates price data from sources including recent fundraising roun=
ds and secondary market bids, offers and sale prices. Trading activity has =
also been slowing as fresh would-be sellers flood the market and spreads be=
tween the price they want for their shares and what buyers are willing to p=
ay continue to widen, according to brokers and investors. In the first quar=
ter of this year, secondary market broker Forge processed 596,000 trades, d=
own 61% from the same period in 2021.=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a disconnect =
between what the buyers are willing to buy at and what the sellers are will=
ing to sell at,=E2=80=9D Forge Chief Operating Officer Jose Cobos told The =
Information. That means people who want to dump certain shares may have to =
temper their expectations even more.And Bloomberg notes:Drops in the value =
of specific companies are emerging in a variety of places. Pandemic darling=
 Instacart Inc. slashed its estimated valuation by almost 40% to $24 billio=
n in March after struggling with decelerating growth. In April, mutual fund=
 giant Fidelity Investments marked down a stake in social media platform Re=
ddit by more than a third. Other once-high-flying private companies includi=
ng Epic Games, Chime and Klarna are trading at discounts ranging from 20% t=
o 60% in secondary markets, data from Next Round Capital show.A theme of th=
is column over the past few years has been that =E2=80=9Cprivate markets ar=
e the new public markets=E2=80=9D: Private companies can now raise lots of =
money without going public, including by selling stock to traditionally pub=
lic investors like D1 and Fidelity, and they can stay private longer as tec=
hnology-driven private marketplaces offer shareholders more opportunities t=
o get liquidity without an initial public offering. The downside of this is=
 that, if your private stock trades in a liquid market among public-type in=
vestors, it can go down: When the market drops, your stock will trade at lo=
wer prices, which is perfectly normal for public markets but is kind of wha=
t private investors are paying to avoid.
 =20
   =20
      Play-to-pay
   =20
 =20
At Bloomberg Businessweek,  Joshua Brustein has a story on Axie Infinity, t=
he =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=80=9D blockchain video game where people can ea=
rn cryptocurrencies by controlling =E2=80=9Ccartoonish blobs distinguished =
by their unique mixture of interchangeable body parts=E2=80=9D that fight e=
ach other and are also non-fungible tokens. The idea is that you pay a bunc=
h of money to buy your starter set of NFT cartoon blobs, and then you play =
and breed (!?) the cartoon blobs to earn more tokens, and ultimately you ge=
t a return on your investment in the form of cryptocurrencies that of cours=
e (1) lose most of their value when people realize that this is a Ponzi sch=
eme and (2) also get stolen from you because that is just how crypto works.=
Anyway those things happened. The advantage of running your Ponzi scheme as=
 a play-to-earn game rather than a straightforward investment opportunity i=
s that, when the scheme collapses, you can pivot from =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=
=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cno no no no no, this is just a game, nobody should be=
 in it for the money, what are you talking about?=E2=80=9D And so Sky Mavis=
 Inc., the company that created Axie Infinity and got robbed of $620 millio=
n, is pivoting:As Sky Mavis=E2=80=99s revolutionary rhetoric began to look =
increasingly hollow, the company shifted its story. In December it quietly =
altered its mission statement, deleting the phrase =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=
=80=9D and replacing it with the mushier =E2=80=9Cplay-and-earn.=E2=80=9D D=
ays after the hack it launched Axie: Origin, a long-awaited new version wit=
h upgraded graphics and tweaks to the gameplay. Crucially, this iteration d=
oesn=E2=80=99t involve cryptocurrencies at all, because Sky Mavis has ackno=
wledged that many players are willing to engage with a new game only if the=
 complications of crypto are removed. The plan is for Origin to supplant th=
e original game, with the noncrypto version attracting a broad base of play=
ers. Of course, Sky Mavis would still also offer a full version with the or=
iginal crypto economy.Company executives are trying to give the impression =
that nothing is wrong, but a clear sense of tension has edged in since Axie=
 token values began to plummet late last year. When I first spoke to Sky Ma=
vis co-founder Jeffrey Zirlin in late January, he told me he was living som=
ewhere in the US but paused when I asked where in the country he was. =E2=
=80=9CI could live anywhere, I don=E2=80=99t usually leave my room,=E2=80=
=9D he said. He did finally give me a more specific location, but asked me =
not to make it public, noting that his team has gotten death threats. =E2=
=80=9CWe have to be careful revealing our location, just like the president=
 doesn=E2=80=99t always have to reveal his location,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=
=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re kind of like heads of state.=E2=80=9DZirlin said he emp=
athized with people who=E2=80=99d lost money=E2=80=94life-changing sums, in=
 some instances. But he added that a crash that got rid of Axie profiteers =
could have its upside, too. =E2=80=9CSometimes having to flush out the peop=
le who are just in it for the money,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=
=99s just the system self-correcting.=E2=80=9DSee imagine if Bernie Madoff =
had said that. =E2=80=9CWhen my clients lose all their money, that=E2=80=99=
s just the system self-correcting.=E2=80=9D Honestly not wrong!=C2=A0Look, =
I think the economics of play-to-earn video games are self-evidently bad. I=
f you are earning money, it has to=C2=A0come from somewhere, and what is Ax=
ie Infinity selling other than the gameplay itself? If 10% of players earn =
money by making the game more fun and exciting for the other 90% of players=
, who pay for a good experience, that=E2=80=99s fine, and there is a long h=
istory of multiplayer games with economics like that, where most people pla=
y for fun but some people have the paid job of making the game more fun for=
 everyone else. But if the game is advertised as a =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=
=80=9D experience, as a route out of poverty, etc., then everyone is playin=
g to make money from each other, which is only sustainable by constantly ad=
ding more new players, and it is a pure Ponzi.=C2=A0But I also think that t=
his is a standard, deep move in web3 economics. We have  talked about this =
 before.=C2=A0Traditional web platforms have =E2=80=9Cnetwork effects=E2=80=
=9D where a thing is more valuable the more people use it; this creates inc=
entives to join the big platforms. But web3 platforms have =E2=80=9Ctoken e=
ffects=E2=80=9D where early adopters get a lot of tokens that represent a s=
ort of equity in the platform; this creates incentives to join platforms ea=
rly. So web3 projects tend to have two=C2=A0related components:=09A decentr=
alized distributed system that (you hope) does something useful, and=09A to=
ken that enables you to use the system and that goes up in value when the s=
ystem becomes more popular.The attraction of any web3 project, early on, wi=
ll be a combination of those two things: You get to use a thing that you th=
ink is good, and also the early adopters will get rich if it takes off. In =
a frenzied crypto boom, the Ponzi element =E2=80=94=C2=A0the prospect of ge=
tting rich if the thing takes off =E2=80=94=C2=A0will tend to dominate, and=
 most people will be in most projects for the money, not for the utility of=
 the underlying thing. But=C2=A0eventually that has to flip; Ponzis can=E2=
=80=99t work forever. If your project gets established enough, if it offers=
 real utility, if people are buying tokens to do the thing that it does rat=
her than to speculate on the tokens going up, then you can transition from=
=C2=A0Ponzi economics to just regular old economics. People will buy the to=
ken because they can use it to do useful stuff, not because they hope more =
people will pile in and they can sell it for a profit.This flip will probab=
ly happen gradually over time, but it might be crystallized in a broad mark=
et crash, and then you might go around saying things like =E2=80=9Csometime=
s having to flush out people who are just in it for the money, that=E2=80=
=99s just the system self-correcting,=E2=80=9D and that will make sense. I =
am not sure it does here.
