om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Redbox?!?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTIvY3J5cHRvLWNyYXNoLWNvbnRhZ2lvbi1jb3VsZC1n=
by1iZXlvbmQtYml0Y29pbi1ldGhlcmV1bS10ZXRoZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNj=
EwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe59ad903" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> talked last month</a> about Redbox Entertainment Inc., a company that (=
1) went public in October 2021 by merging with a special purpose acquisitio=
n company at $10 per share, (2) traded as high as $17.93, (3) then traded d=
own to $5.60, (4) then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2=
FyL2RhdGEvMTgyMDIwMS8wMDAxMTA0NjU5MjIwNTg2MDUvdG0yMjE1MDMxZDFfOGsuaHRt/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f6776b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">agreed to be acquired</a> by Chicken=
 Soup for the Soul Entertainment Inc. for about $0.69 per share in stock, a=
n 88% discount to its trading price, and (5) then traded down to $2.58 per =
share. That was weird! Two weird things were:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-ty=
pe: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Why would the company agree to sell=C2=A0for $0.69 per share wh=
en it was trading at $5.60? (=E2=80=9CWe were bringing assets that were hel=
pful in terms of the debt, cleaning up of the capital structure, access to =
new cash,=E2=80=9D Chicken Soup=E2=80=99s chief executive officer <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTEvY2hpY2tlbi1zb3Vw=
LWJ1eXMtYXBvbGxvLWJhY2tlZC1yZWRib3gtYXMtc3BhYy1tYXJrZXQtc3B1dHRlcnM_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB39032568" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">  sort of explained</a>.)</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Why would people=C2=A0<em>buy stock for $2.58=C2=A0</em>=
when it is going to be merged out of existence at $0.69?</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might have told a story like =E2=80=9Cthe deal won=
=E2=80=99t close and the stock will shoot up as people realize the great va=
lue of an independent Redbox,=E2=80=9D but there is no evidence for that; i=
n fact Redbox=E2=80=99s controlling shareholders had approved the deal so t=
he odds of it falling apart are low.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you=
 might have told a story like =E2=80=9Cthe stock will trade down to $0.69 a=
s people realize what is happening,=E2=80=9D but that story would have been=
 wrong. Redbox has <em>rallied</em>. It=C2=A0closed at $9.47 yesterday, and=
 was up again this morning; at noon today it was trading at about $12.89 on=
 heavy volume, tons of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9zZWFyY2g_cT0lMjRyZGJ4JnNyYz=
10eXBlZF9xdWVyeQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf83ac60e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">social-media en=
thusiasm</a>=C2=A0and absolutely no news. Meanwhile Chicken Soup=E2=80=99s =
stock hasn=E2=80=99t done much; it closed yesterday at $7.31, making=C2=A0t=
he merger consideration =E2=80=94=C2=A00.087 Chicken Soup shares per Redbox=
 share =E2=80=94=C2=A0worth about $0.64 per Redbox share. You can buy a Red=
box share for $12.89 today, and when the merger closes you=E2=80=99ll get 0=
.087 Chicken Soup shares. Or you can buy a whole Chicken Soup share today f=
or $7.31, and when the merger closes you=E2=80=99ll still have a whole Chic=
ken Soup share. One Chicken Soup share, which you can buy for $7.31, is wor=
th about 11 times as much as 0.087 Chicken Soup shares, which you can buy f=
or $12.89. Why?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I dunno. But there ar=
e two lessons here. One is that the essential function of a meme stock is t=
o be a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.28=
5603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMj=
UvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZ=
Gl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjEwJnV0bV9jYW1w=
YWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b1e574e" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Schelling =
point</a>: A meme stock is=C2=A0a stock that you want to buy because other =
people want to buy it. How a stock becomes a meme stock is, to me, a myster=
ious process, but there is no obvious reason that =E2=80=9Cpeople think it =
has a lot of fundamental value=E2=80=9D would be a particularly important p=
art of the process. (Really, =E2=80=9Ca stock that you buy because other pe=
ople want to buy it because it has good long-term cash flows=E2=80=9D is th=
e opposite of a meme stock; that=E2=80=99s just a regular stock.)=C2=A0You =
want your meme stocks to be=C2=A0<em>fun</em>; you want the story to be viv=
id; you want the online discussions where you egg each other on to buy the =
stock to have a sense of drama and comedy. At Quartz last month, Scott Nove=
r wrote an article titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly9xei5jb20vMjE2ODg2Mi9yZWRib3gtaX=
MtdGhlLWR1bWJlc3QtbWVtZS1zdG9jay15ZXQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb9cdba43" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">Redbox is the dumbest meme stock yet</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Reddit, there=E2=80=99s been chatter about a =
short squeeze, but only about 29% of Redbox=E2=80=99s public float has been=
 sold short, according to data published by FactSet. Short squeezes work wh=
en so much of a company=E2=80=99s stock is shorted that when buyers drive i=
t up, shorts have to re-enter the market by buying new shares to cover thei=
r own loss, sending the stock even higher. (By contrast, 140% of GameStop=
=E2=80=99s float was shorted when retail traders took it to the moon in Jan=
uary 2021.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the sale to Chicken Soup f=
or the Soul closes in the next few months, Redbox stockholders will be paid=
 out at $.49 a share. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t see any scenario where an in=
vestor could make money, aside from the greater fool theory,=E2=80=9D one f=
inancial analyst told Yahoo Finance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In oth=
er words, retailers might be pumping the stock and hoping to get out before=
 the dumping starts. This trading activity appears to have nothing to do wi=
th movies, streaming, or large red vending machines. Like other consumer-fa=
cing companies that tap into retail trader nostalgia=E2=80=94like GameStop,=
 AMC, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, Blackberry, and even Blockbuster=E2=80=94Redbo=
x is just another momentary Wall Street meme. At least this one has an expi=
ration date when the deal closes.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Those attributes are all bad for, like, rational stock value, but good =
for memes:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Trading the dumbest mem=
e stock is much funnier than trading the forty-sixth-dumbest meme stock. Re=
dbox is a very funny meme stock! If you tell a traditional finance person =
=E2=80=9CI am buying GameStop at $300,=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Chmm =
that seems high I dunno.=E2=80=9D If you tell them =E2=80=9CI am buying Red=
box at $12.89=E2=80=9D they will sputter and twitch and try to prove to you=
 with math=C2=A0that it=E2=80=99s a mistake. That=E2=80=99s funnier!</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Having an expiration date makes this g=
ame more exciting and sillier. The problem with a regular meme stock is tha=
t eventually people will get bored; the finite expiration date here limits =
that risk. The game has to end, and when it does, someone will be holding q=
uite a bag. It creates more immediate danger and excitement than a meme sto=
ck that could keep going up forever.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Also to be fair once the deal closes you could aways meme up the Chicken So=
up stock, why not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other lesson=C2=A0is=
 that the essential condition of a meme stock is limits to arbitrage. Any r=
easonable person would look at this price action and say: =E2=80=9CI should=
 short 1 million shares of Redbox for $9.47, collecting $9.47 million; then=
 I should buy 87,000 shares of Chicken Soup for $7.31, spending $636,000, a=
nd then when the merger happens I will deliver those Chicken Soup shares to=
 close out my short and keep my $8.8 million of nearly risk-free profit.=E2=
=80=9D But a sensible person would have said that back when Redbox was trad=
ing at $2.58 last month, and if they had done that trade then, it would hav=
e moved against them by millions of dollars by now and they probably would =
have been liquidated at a huge loss. Because there is no cap on the price o=
f a meme stock, it is risky and unpleasant to short one, and there is at le=
ast one high-profile case of a multibillion-dollar hedge fund <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTkvcmVkZGl0LXMtd2FsbHN0cm=
VldGJldHMtY2VsZWJyYXRlcy1pbXBsb3Npb24tb2YtZ2FiZS1wbG90a2luLXMtbWVsdmluLWhlZ=
GdlLWZ1bmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1f=
c291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZ=
m/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d676dd9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> closing down</a> due to exces=
sive shorting of meme stocks. Why bother, on a stock this small? (Also, rel=
atedly, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.2=
85603/aHR0cHM6Ly9maW50ZWwuaW8vc3MvdXMvcmRieA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f785=
aec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">stock borrow</a> in Redbox is scarce and expensive, so it=E2=
=80=99s not exactly easy and costless to do this trade. Also, I mean, the m=
erger <em>could=C2=A0</em>fall apart.) And so there are meme-y buyers to pu=
sh Redbox up, and no rational sellers to push it down, and the price spiral=
s up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advanced move here would be for R=
edbox to do an at-the-market offering, selling a bunch of shares for $9.47 =
each to raise extremely cheap cash for its soon-to-be owners at Chicken Sou=
p. I think that would be a bit too much? Other meme stocks have <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDMvYW1jLWhhcy1hLWJp=
dC1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB459e3d62" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> done at-the-=
market offerings</a>, and the US Securities and Exchange Commission has <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDkvdGhlLXNl=
Yy13YW50cy1yZWRkaXQtbWVtZS1zdG9ja3MtdG8tYWRtaXQtdGhleS1yZS1kYW5nZXJvdXM_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDYxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBec34073f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> grumbled but allowed it</a>. The SEC doesn=
=E2=80=99t <em>like=C2=A0</em>it when companies sell shares=C2=A0to excited=
 retail investors for more than they=E2=80=99re worth, but it can=E2=80=99t=
 really police that; worth is subjective, and you can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>pr=
ove=C2=A0</em>that the shares are selling for more than they=E2=80=99re wor=
th.=C2=A0Doing an at-the-market offering at $9.47 when you=E2=80=99ve signe=
d a merger agreement to sell for $0.69 probably goes too far though.</p><ta=
