<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Private markets are the new public markets</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One widely accepted theory in financia=
l markets is that liquid things are worth more than illiquid things. If you=
 know that you can sell an asset quickly for roughly its fair price, you wi=
ll be happier about buying it, so you will pay more for it. Classically, pr=
ivate companies are supposed to become more valuable when they go public: Y=
ou can trade public stock on the stock exchange relatively easily, which sh=
ould make it more valuable than illiquid private-company stock.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a countervailing theory, one that <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTItMjAveW91LWQtcGF5LW5v=
dC10by1zZWUteW91ci1zdG9jay1wcmljZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MTAmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0a75836f" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I ass=
ociate</a> with <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28=
017010.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXFyLmNvbS9JbnNpZ2h0cy9QZXJzcGVjdGl2ZXMvVGhlL=
UlsbGlxdWlkaXR5LURpc2NvdW50/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7c1a22a" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Clif=
f Asness</a>, that holds that illiquid things are worth more than liquid th=
ings. The theory here is that investors do not like=C2=A0<em>volatility</em=
>; they prefer steady returns to wild price swings. Stocks that trade frequ=
ently in liquid public markets=C2=A0<em>look=C2=A0</em>volatile: Sometimes =
they go up, but sometimes they go down. Private-company stocks=C2=A0<em>don=
=E2=80=99t look volatile</em>, because they don=E2=80=99t trade much, and w=
hen they do it is often in carefully orchestrated ways that give the impres=
sion of steadily increasing prices. (Most people who buy private-company st=
ocks buy them from the company in organized funding rounds, and if the mark=
et is bad the company just won=E2=80=99t raise money.) An investor who want=
s returns with low volatility will prefer (and overpay for) illiquid assets=
: When times are good, the prices of those assets will go up and you will h=
ave a gain; when times are bad, they won=E2=80=99t trade and you won=E2=80=
=99t have to recognize a loss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so when =
the market for tech stocks goes down, the market for=C2=A0<em>private=C2=A0=
</em>tech companies =E2=80=A6=C2=A0also goes down, in some economic sense (=
it is harder for those companies to raise money), but arguably <em>doesn=E2=
