 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Joshua Brustein has a story</a> on Axie Infinity, the =
=E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=80=9D blockchain video game where people can earn =
cryptocurrencies by controlling =E2=80=9Ccartoonish blobs distinguished by =
their unique mixture of interchangeable body parts=E2=80=9D that fight each=
 other and are also non-fungible tokens. The idea is that you pay a bunch o=
f money to buy your starter set of NFT cartoon blobs, and then you play and=
 breed (!?) the cartoon blobs to earn more tokens, and ultimately you get a=
 return on your investment in the form of cryptocurrencies that of course (=
1) lose most of their value when people realize that this is a Ponzi scheme=
 and (2) also get stolen from you because that is just how crypto works.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway those things happened. The advantage o=
f running your Ponzi scheme as a play-to-earn game rather than a straightfo=
rward investment opportunity is that, when the scheme collapses, you can pi=
vot from =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cno no no no no, this is=
 just a game, nobody should be in it for the money, what are you talking ab=
out?=E2=80=9D And so Sky Mavis Inc., the company that created Axie Infinity=
 and got robbed of $620 million, is pivoting:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">As Sky Mavis=E2=80=99s revolutionary rhetoric began to look =
increasingly hollow, the company shifted its story. In December it quietly =
altered its mission statement, deleting the phrase =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=
=80=9D and replacing it with the mushier =E2=80=9Cplay-and-earn.=E2=80=9D D=
ays after the hack it launched Axie: Origin, a long-awaited new version wit=
h upgraded graphics and tweaks to the gameplay. Crucially, this iteration d=
oesn=E2=80=99t involve cryptocurrencies at all, because Sky Mavis has ackno=
wledged that many players are willing to engage with a new game only if the=
 complications of crypto are removed. The plan is for Origin to supplant th=
e original game, with the noncrypto version attracting a broad base of play=
ers. Of course, Sky Mavis would still also offer a full version with the or=
iginal crypto economy.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Company executives a=
re trying to give the impression that nothing is wrong, but a clear sense o=
f tension has edged in since Axie token values began to plummet late last y=
ear. When I first spoke to Sky Mavis co-founder Jeffrey Zirlin in late Janu=
ary, he told me he was living somewhere in the US but paused when I asked w=
here in the country he was. =E2=80=9CI could live anywhere, I don=E2=80=99t=
 usually leave my room,=E2=80=9D he said. He did finally give me a more spe=
cific location, but asked me not to make it public, noting that his team ha=
s gotten death threats. =E2=80=9CWe have to be careful revealing our locati=
on, just like the president doesn=E2=80=99t always have to reveal his locat=
ion,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re kind of like heads of state.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Zirlin said he empathized with pe=
ople who=E2=80=99d lost money=E2=80=94life-changing sums, in some instances=
. But he added that a crash that got rid of Axie profiteers could have its =
upside, too. =E2=80=9CSometimes having to flush out the people who are just=
 in it for the money,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s just the sy=
stem self-correcting.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>See imagine if Bernie Madoff had said that. =E2=80=9CWhen my clients lose =
all their money, that=E2=80=99s just the system self-correcting.=E2=80=9D H=
onestly not wrong!=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, I think the =
economics of play-to-earn video games are self-evidently bad. If you are ea=
rning money, it has to=C2=A0<em>come from somewhere</em>, and what is Axie =
Infinity selling other than the gameplay itself? If 10% of players earn mon=
ey by making the game more fun and exciting for the other 90% of players, w=
ho pay for a good experience, that=E2=80=99s fine, and there is a long hist=
ory of multiplayer games with economics like that, where most people play f=
or fun but some people have the paid job of making the game more fun for ev=
eryone else. But if the game is advertised as a =E2=80=9Cplay-to-earn=E2=80=
=9D experience, as a route out of poverty, etc., then everyone is playing t=
o make money from each other, which is only sustainable by constantly addin=
g more new players, and it is a pure Ponzi.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">But I also think that this is a standard, deep move in web3 economic=
s. We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2801701=
0.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMD=
